{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1e33362d-27a9-439a-b9db-99b6f5d20678","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to **abstract file I/O behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into classes that need it. In production, provide a thin wrapper over `System.IO`; in tests, use a mock or in-memory implementation.\n\n**Alternatively**, use the [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) NuGet package, which provides `IFileSystem` out of the box along with a `MockFileSystem` for testing:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```\n\n```csharp\n// Production\nservices.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();\n\n// Test\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>\n{\n    { \"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{}\") }\n});\nvar sut = new MyService(fs);\n```\n\nThis is the most common and well-supported pattern. It avoids touching the real filesystem in tests and makes behavior easy to verify.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d2f1a1a-875f-4529-a374-b6b9ad8da939","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a common software design question about abstraction and dependency injection.\n\nLet me give a concise answer about the best practices for making file system operations testable in .NET.","outputTokens":411,"requestId":"BC43:2E7316:1E0D9DD:21840CB:69FA9C07"},"id":"7f47c1ad-fe9e-4ead-8ece-c8d65eb4a638","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:40:32.213Z","parentId":"f6567f5b-6d1f-49fa-bd97-45aec389a58d"}
